1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:11,983
You're listening to: llms.txt, GEO and AI Search: How Developers Get Cited by ChatGPT, Perplexity & Google AI Mode (2026).

2
00:00:11,983 --> 00:00:21,225
Generative Engine Optimization (GEO) is how your content gets cited inside ChatGPT, Perplexity, Claude, and Google AI Overviews.

3
00:00:21,225 --> 00:00:37,560
This developer-focused guide covers llms.txt and llms-full.txt, AI crawler policies, IndexNow, answer-first content structure, and the entity signals that drive AI citations in 2026 — with working code.

4
00:00:37,560 --> 00:00:38,629
Let's get started.

5
00:00:38,629 --> 00:00:54,399
Generative Engine Optimization (GEO) is the practice of making your content retrievable, quotable, and attributable by AI search systems — ChatGPT search, Perplexity, Claude, Bing Copilot, and Google's AI Overviews/AI Mode.

6
00:00:54,399 --> 00:01:08,461
In 2026 this matters because the click economics changed: AI Overviews alone cut traditional CTR dramatically, but pages that get cited inside AI answers earn measurably more clicks than pages that merely rank.

7
00:01:08,461 --> 00:01:20,516
The overlap between "ranks in the top 10" and "gets cited by AI" has dropped to roughly 17–38% — meaning AI citation is now a separate game you have to play deliberately.

8
00:01:20,516 --> 00:01:26,250
The good news for developers: most of GEO is infrastructure, and you can ship it in an afternoon.

9
00:01:26,250 --> 00:01:29,302
Here's the complete stack I run in production, with code.

10
00:01:29,302 --> 00:01:33,353
Now, let's talk about What is llms.txt and do you need one?.

11
00:01:33,353 --> 00:01:44,314
llms.txt is a proposed standard (llmstxt.org): a markdown file at your site root that gives LLMs a curated, token-efficient map of your site.

12
00:01:44,314 --> 00:01:48,834
Think of it as a sitemap written for a language model instead of a crawler:

13
00:01:48,834 --> 00:01:57,644
The format is strict on purpose: an H1 with your name, a blockquote summary, then H2 sections of links with one-line descriptions.

14
00:01:57,644 --> 00:02:04,206
The blockquote is the part most LLMs quote verbatim when describing you — write it like the answer you want repeated.

15
00:02:04,206 --> 00:02:12,908
Note: Google has said llms.txt is not required for AI Overviews, and that's true — Google uses its regular index.

16
00:02:12,908 --> 00:02:19,951
But ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity, and dozens of agent frameworks do fetch it when reasoning about a domain.

17
00:02:19,951 --> 00:02:21,971
It costs one static file.

18
00:02:21,971 --> 00:02:22,716
Ship it.

19
00:02:22,716 --> 00:02:27,127
Moving on to What is llms-full.txt and how do you generate it?.

20
00:02:27,127 --> 00:02:38,425
llms-full.txt is the companion file: the full text of your content in one plain-text document, so an LLM can ingest everything without crawling page by page.

21
00:02:38,425 --> 00:02:41,682
Don't maintain it by hand — generate it at build time.

22
00:02:41,682 --> 00:02:44,915
In Next.js App Router, that's a route handler:

23
00:02:44,915 --> 00:02:51,562
Mine compiles 80+ posts into a ~2 MB file on every deploy and never goes stale.

24
00:02:51,562 --> 00:02:55,312
The force-static export means it costs nothing at request time.

25
00:02:55,312 --> 00:02:59,831
Next up: Which AI crawlers should you allow in robots.txt?.

26
00:02:59,831 --> 00:03:03,389
This is the highest-leverage five minutes in GEO.

27
00:03:03,389 --> 00:03:10,961
Each AI product uses distinct user agents, and several are blocked by default in popular robots.txt templates.

28
00:03:10,961 --> 00:03:13,629
The ones that matter in 2026:

29
00:03:13,629 --> 00:03:16,177
User agent, Powers, If you block it.

30
00:03:16,177 --> 00:03:22,548
OAI-SearchBot, ChatGPT search citations, Invisible in ChatGPT web answers.

31
00:03:22,548 --> 00:03:27,283
GPTBot, OpenAI training, Not in future model knowledge.

32
00:03:27,283 --> 00:03:34,375
ClaudeBot / Claude-SearchBot, Anthropic indexing & search, Invisible to Claude users.

33
00:03:34,375 --> 00:03:40,649
PerplexityBot / Perplexity-User, Perplexity answers, No Perplexity citations.

34
00:03:40,649 --> 00:03:45,673
Google-Extended, Gemini grounding, Reduced Gemini visibility.

35
00:03:45,673 --> 00:03:49,879
Bingbot, Bing + Copilot, Invisible to Copilot.

36
00:03:49,879 --> 00:03:54,302
Amazonbot, Alexa / Rufus, No Alexa answers.

37
00:03:54,302 --> 00:03:58,858
Meta-ExternalAgent, Meta AI, No Meta AI citations.

38
00:03:58,858 --> 00:04:09,639
The distinction worth knowing: GPTBot is the training crawler, OAI-SearchBot is the search crawler, and ChatGPT-User is the live browsing agent acting for a user.

39
00:04:09,639 --> 00:04:15,444
You can allow search and browsing while blocking training if that's your policy — they're independent rules.

40
00:04:15,444 --> 00:04:21,237
For a personal brand or product site, I allow all of them: maximum surface area is the point.

41
00:04:21,237 --> 00:04:25,444
Let's explore How does IndexNow get you into Bing and Copilot faster?.

42
00:04:25,444 --> 00:04:35,612
Bing powers ChatGPT's underlying web index and Microsoft Copilot, which makes Bing indexing an AI-visibility play, not just a search one.

43
00:04:35,612 --> 00:04:43,774
IndexNow is Bing/Yandex's push protocol — instead of waiting for a crawl, you POST your URLs the moment they change:

44
00:04:43,826 --> 00:04:57,850
You verify ownership with a key file in public/, then curl -X POST https://yoursite.com/api/indexnow after each deploy (or wire it into CI).

45
00:04:57,850 --> 00:05:04,917
My last submission pushed 194 URLs and all three endpoints returned success in under a second.

46
00:05:04,917 --> 00:05:10,795
Google does not use IndexNow — for Google you still rely on sitemaps and Search Console.

47
00:05:10,795 --> 00:05:14,833
Now let's look at How do you structure content so AI engines quote it?.

48
00:05:14,833 --> 00:05:21,840
The 2026 citation data is unusually specific, and it converges on a few mechanical rules:

49
00:05:21,840 --> 00:05:23,667
Answer first, then expand.

50
00:05:23,667 --> 00:05:29,581
AI extraction favors pages where the H1 or first paragraph contains a complete answer.

51
00:05:29,581 --> 00:05:34,797
Mirror the question in your heading, answer it in 1–2 sentences, then go deep.

52
00:05:34,797 --> 00:05:40,446
(Notice every H2 in this post is a question with the answer in the first sentence below it.

53
00:05:40,446 --> 00:05:41,985
That's not a style choice.)

54
00:05:41,985 --> 00:05:46,348
Write self-contained passages of 100–300 words.

55
00:05:46,348 --> 00:05:53,223
Extracted AI Overview passages cluster at 134–167 words.

56
00:05:53,223 --> 00:06:00,602
A passage that depends on context three paragraphs up doesn't get quoted — every section should survive being read alone.

57
00:06:00,602 --> 00:06:07,333
This is what the GEO literature calls semantic completeness, and it's the strongest single predictor of citation.

58
00:06:07,333 --> 00:06:09,797
Put a labeled TL;DR at the top.

59
00:06:09,797 --> 00:06:15,638
An explicit summary block adjacent to the H1 is the easiest possible extraction target.

60
00:06:15,638 --> 00:06:21,011
I render every post's description as a visible TL;DR card for exactly this reason.

61
00:06:21,011 --> 00:06:23,727
Use tables and lists for comparable facts.

62
00:06:23,727 --> 00:06:36,420
Structured comparisons get lifted into AI answers far more often than the same facts buried in prose — pages combining text, structured data, and media see dramatically higher selection rates.

63
00:06:36,420 --> 00:06:37,922
Be a named entity.

64
00:06:37,922 --> 00:06:51,408
Citations skew heavily toward sources with strong E-E-A-T: a Person schema with an @id, a visible author bio, consistent facts about you across pages, and sameAs links to GitHub/LinkedIn.

65
00:06:51,408 --> 00:06:56,203
AI systems resolve who is saying this before deciding whether to repeat it.

66
00:06:56,203 --> 00:07:01,985
The structured-data half of this is covered in my technical SEO guide for Next.js.

67
00:07:01,985 --> 00:07:05,506
Now, let's talk about How do you measure whether GEO is actually working?.

68
00:07:05,506 --> 00:07:10,134
Until June 2026 the honest answer was "you mostly can't."

69
00:07:10,134 --> 00:07:20,807
That changed on June 3, 2026, when Google launched Generative AI performance reports in Search Console — the first official data on AI visibility.

70
00:07:20,807 --> 00:07:34,629
The new report shows impressions your URLs earn inside AI Overviews and AI Mode (and AI features in Discover), broken down by page, country, device, and date, at granularity down to hourly.

71
00:07:34,629 --> 00:07:41,864
No click data yet, but for the first time you can see which pages AI answers actually pull from — and which never get selected.

72
00:07:41,864 --> 00:07:49,857
The rollout is staged (UK first, then global), so check Search Console periodically until the report appears for your property.

73
00:07:49,857 --> 00:08:02,393
When it does, treat it like any other funnel metric: pages with search impressions but zero AI impressions are your optimization backlog — usually they fail the semantic-completeness test from the previous section.

74
00:08:02,393 --> 00:08:05,122
Two companion signals to track alongside it:

75
00:08:05,122 --> 00:08:12,081
Bing Webmaster Tools already reports IndexNow submission status and Copilot-adjacent visibility..

76
00:08:12,081 --> 00:08:18,451
Server logs — grep for OAI-SearchBot, ClaudeBot, and PerplexityBot user agents.

77
00:08:18,451 --> 00:08:26,648
Crawl frequency from these bots is a leading indicator of AI-surface inclusion; if they never fetch you, you can't be cited..

78
00:08:26,648 --> 00:08:36,071
Warning: Google's June 2026 update also shipped an opt-out toggle that removes your site from AI Overviews and AI Mode entirely.

79
00:08:36,071 --> 00:08:37,730
It defaults to opted-in.

80
00:08:37,730 --> 00:08:49,100
If you're doing GEO, never touch it — sites that opt out get zero AI impressions and zero AI traffic, and Google has confirmed the toggle doesn't affect classic rankings either way.

81
00:08:49,100 --> 00:08:52,069
Moving on to What does a complete GEO stack look like?.

82
00:08:52,069 --> 00:08:54,785
The full checklist, all shippable in code:

83
00:08:54,842 --> 00:08:59,996
public/llms.txt — curated index, hand-written.

84
00:08:59,996 --> 00:09:05,765
/llms-full.txt — full content, generated each build.

85
00:09:05,765 --> 00:09:13,337
robots.txt allowing OAI-SearchBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot, Google-Extended, Bingbot and friends.

86
00:09:13,337 --> 00:09:18,085
IndexNow endpoint + post-deploy ping (Bing/Yandex/Copilot).

87
00:09:18,085 --> 00:09:23,722
JSON-LD entity graph: Person with @id, BlogPosting, BreadcrumbList.

88
00:09:23,722 --> 00:09:28,025
Answer-first headings, TL;DR blocks, self-contained sections.

89
00:09:28,025 --> 00:09:31,558
Visible author identity and honest updated dates.

90
00:09:31,558 --> 00:09:36,342
RSS feed (several AI crawlers use it for freshness discovery).

91
00:09:36,342 --> 00:09:45,465
Search Console Generative AI report monitored monthly (live since June 2026); AI opt-out toggle left untouched.

92
00:09:45,465 --> 00:09:56,258
None of this replaces traditional SEO — Google's AI Overviews still draw from the regular index, so Core Web Vitals and rendering performance still gate everything.

93
00:09:56,258 --> 00:10:02,159
GEO is a layer on top: same content, made legible to a new class of reader.

94
00:10:02,159 --> 00:10:07,231
The sites winning AI citations in 2026 aren't doing anything mystical.

95
00:10:07,231 --> 00:10:16,979
They made themselves easy to retrieve, easy to quote, and easy to attribute — and they did it before their competitors thought of AI search as a channel at all.

96
00:10:16,979 --> 00:10:18,662
And that's the end of this article.

97
00:10:18,662 --> 00:10:19,755
Thanks for listening.

